{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018VttP9X7GTNr3G3BAefWR8","type":"tool_result","content":"1700\t- Cross-phase: Some files were certainly read by multiple subagents (schema file, test file), but since subagents are isolated this is expected and unavoidable.\n1701\t\n1702\t**What the numbers say:**\n1703\t- 67 tool calls for a full story lifecycle is lean. Prior sessions averaged ~70-100 calls per story.\n1704\t- No subagent needed retries or restarts.\n1705\t- create-story was read-heavy (9 Read, 5 Grep) ŌĆö expected for a story creation phase that must gather context.\n1706\t- dev-story was edit-heavy (5 Edit, 2 Write) ŌĆö expected for implementation.\n1707\t- code-review was balanced (9 Bash for running tests, 7 Edit for fixes) ŌĆö the review found and fixed real bugs.\n1708\t\n1709\t### Cost Trend\n1710\t\n1711\t| Session | Stories | Est. Cost | Cost/Story | Efficiency |\n1712\t|---------|---------|-----------|------------|------------|\n1713\t| 7 (earlier today) | 5 (2-1 through 2-5) | ~$24 | ~$4.80 | Baseline |\n1714\t| 8 (this session) | 1 (3-1) | ~$4-5 | ~$4-5 | Comparable |\n1715\t\n1716\tCost per story remains stable. The verification phase continues to be the most expensive (~44% of total spend across all sessions), but this session had no verification format failures ŌĆö a first.\n1717\t\n1718\t---\n1719\t\n1720\t## 4. What Went Well\n1721\t\n1722\t- **Zero retries.** Story went create -> dev -> code-review -> verification -> done without a single retry or failure. First session with zero wasted iterations.\n1723\t- **Code review found real bugs.** 3 MEDIUM schema validation gaps (empty strings, empty arrays, missing required traits) were caught and fixed before verification. The code review phase justified its cost.\n1724\t- **39 tests, 100% coverage on target module.** Test-provable ACs produced thorough test coverage without manual intervention.\n1725\t- **Clean session issues log.** No HIGH-severity issues. The dev-story phase reported zero issues ŌĆö a first.\n1726\t- **No verification format failures.** Previous sessions had 3+ rewrites for proof document formatting. This session: zero. The format instructions may have been internalized or improved.\n1727\t- **67 tool calls total** ŌĆö leanest full-lifecycle story execution so far.\n1728\t- **Subagent file reads were non-redundant** within each phase. 27 unique files across 27 reads.\n1729\t\n1730\t---\n1731\t\n1732\t## 5. What Went Wrong\n1733\t\n1734\t- **`codeharness stats --save` failed** due to missing `session-logs/` directory. This is the same fragility reported in 6 of 8 sessions. Cost analysis had to be done from the cumulative report + manual estimation.\n1735\t- **AGENTS.md stale** ŌĆö still missing entries from story 2-5 (validate-schema.ts, validate-self.ts). This caused `codeharness verify` precondition to fail. Not blocking but accumulating tech debt.\n1736\t- **`_bmad/config.yaml` path confusion** recurred (5th time). Still not fixed.\n1737\t- **2 redundant coverage runs** across code-review and verification phases. Minor waste (~$0.30-0.50).\n1738\t\n1739\t---\n1740\t\n1741\t## 6. Lessons Learned\n1742\t\n1743\t### Patterns to Repeat\n1744\t\n1745\t1. **Test-provable ACs are the fastest path.** All 8 ACs were test-provable, which meant verification was mechanical (run tests, check output). No subjective evaluation needed. Stories with mixed verification types take 2-3x longer.\n1746\t2. **Schema-definition stories are ideal early-sprint targets.** Pure schema + validation function stories have clear boundaries, no integration risk, and high test coverage naturally. Good warm-up for Epic 3.\n1747\t3. **Code review catching schema gaps before verification saves money.** The 3 MEDIUM bugs found by review would have caused verification failures and retries if uncaught. The ~$3 review cost prevented ~$8-12 in retry costs.\n1748\t\n1749\t### Patterns to Avoid"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01D1aPv265mgJjX6WrHHertR","session_id":"605a3302-c654-40ea-969b-1ce171500852","uuid":"abecd87d-cb05-4142-8b0e-308f969da0dc","timestamp":"2026-04-02T19:24:25.048Z"}
